text: Okay, maybe we can start by having you share with me how were you first recruited into the MN program in 2013 if I'm not wrong. How ah? So basically I expressed interest to further my studies and I was given two options lah. Basically either geriatrics or palliative. At that point of time I think they needed another palliative APS so I was allowed to attach to the palliative team and there I gained one year of experience then after that I went to study lah. But what was that mode of communication that you expressed interest? So they were, so basically they were, I think they opened application for advanced diploma so I applied for it. But then I think my supervisor then, I mean at that point of time he felt that maybe no need to go through advanced, just go for masters directly lah. But at that point of time because we were the first batch so the career progression and education path wasn't very clear. So that's why, I mean from his point of view he felt that it wasn't necessary to go through advanced degree lah so he asked me to explore the option of going for MN program. When you said you are the first batch, what does it mean? So I'm like the first batch of NUS degree nursing graduates. So that was why you felt that the career progression at that point of time wasn't very clear. Okay then following, expressing interest and speaking to your nurse leader about entering this MN program, did they prepare you or speak to you about anything? So basically I think one of the admission criteria into MN was to have some prior clinical experience in the field of specialty. So I was given the opportunity to join the apprentice team in the hospital for about 6 months to a year and to see whether it was an appropriate fit and also whether I enjoyed that discipline. So was there some kind of a selection interview or recruitment interview that you had to go through in order to get this sponsorship from your hospital? Yes, there was a selection interview. So maybe can you speak a bit about that selection interview based on whatever you can remember? I think a page based panel interview with nursing leaders and HR senior management, I think they were more interested as to why I wanted to study and why I would like to consider palliative medicine or geriatric as an area of specialty. I think these are the two main, I mean the questions around these two main focus. At that point of time, did they ask you about your plans for settling down, having a family and all that? No, because I was single then. Oh I see, okay. But now if you think about it, about the recruitment of RNs into the MM programme, do you think it's easier to be selected if you are male or female? No, I don't think gender makes a difference. Why? I feel that, I mean first of all, I think the nursing population is actually majority female. Then secondly, I also feel that, I mean the feel that I get during the interview and during the selection process was more of a merit based rather than your demographic. In terms of merit, I think it's a good thing. What are the merits they were looking at? Like for example, your years of mental experience, your TPMs and then your GPA from your undergrad studies and also, I think basically what performance of, rather than the gender profile. Do you have any colleagues or fellow APN colleagues where they had to defer? I'm speaking for both male and female APN colleagues. Do they have to defer like family planning to pursue the MM programme? I think even if they do make plans to defer, it's actually an individual decision. I mean really a personal decision rather than something that is driven by the institution. Are you trying to imply that nursing leaders do not take into consideration the gender of the RN when nominating him or her into the programme? Yes. Okay. In that case right, because as you mentioned just now, there are so few males, RNs on the ground working, then isn't it easier for them to be identified if they excel in a certain way or do a bit better in their clinical practice? I mean I still feel like, I mean after working in a ward and then also like now sometimes I'm working in a ward and managing some of the staff, I don't feel that like the gender makes any difference when you appraise the staff. It's really by their ability and capability. Yeah. So even though like by gender they look like they are easier to identify, but I think at the end, when we think about the rigourness of the MM programme, I think it has to be based on I guess capability and ability rather than gender. I understand that you are now, yes you are an APN but you also have a job title of an NC. So I'm just wondering, do you play any role in appraisals? Okay so basically I'm also, because I'm based in our acute palliative ward in the hospital itself. So basically I do work with all the staff on the ground and I work very closely with their supervisors like the nurse clinician and the nurse manager of the ward. And of course sometimes they do ask for my input in terms of their contribution during our multidisciplinary rounds, during daily ward rounds and also how their assessment are like when they are managing their patients. So yeah because of this exposure, I get to work with many nurses on the ground in the ward and thankfully in my ward there are actually quite a handful of males, like I think three or four of them in the ward. So when I work with both the females and males in the ward, I don't feel like the gender per se affects how I would assess them but rather their ability to perform at work. So based on your interactions with your fellow colleagues, the NMs, I'm talking about the NMs and the ward MTs right, when they have to do a TPM for their staff or when they have to think of professional development of their staff, do you feel that there are gender biases? I don't feel so. Okay. Why though? I mean I have seen males in management roles, in clinical roles and in research roles and also in education roles. And I feel that when they are all in these different roles, they do fit the profile of this career path. They like to teach or they are very into research or they are someone who likes to pursue administrative stuff. So I feel that when I work with these male colleagues of these different nursing career paths, they do suit the profile and I don't see a particular career path where there are more males than the other. Okay. That's a very good point. Okay, then I'm just going to draw some general statements. In the corporate world right, where there is more male domination, there's more proportion of men, there's a tendency for gender bias to occur where they favour men and put men in leadership and all that. But how do you think this translates in nursing? Like in nursing, there is a much greater proportion of females. Do you think there is this female dominance occurring or there's this bias towards female, like putting females in leadership and preferring females to take bigger roles in nursing? Okay, I don't feel that the gender affects or causes any bias to any particular nursing career path. The only, I don't know whether it's appropriate or not, but I think the only limitation that I have observed is that the male nurses probably would not be able to nurse female patients and that is difficult to allocate them to, I say it's difficult to allocate their work loads. I mean, so far that's the limitation that I've observed. But otherwise, I don't feel, I mean even though nursing itself is female dominant, I don't feel like it means that for you to progress through the career path, you have to be a female. Yeah, I mean that's good. It also shows how there are equal opportunities for both gender in nursing right? Yeah. Then in that case, at this present moment, do you have any male APN colleagues? In the hospital or as general? Yeah, you can talk about your hospital first. I mean in my hospital, there isn't one now, but there is one who is in training. And I mean, if you talk about my MN class, there isn't any male. There isn't? There isn't any. Not even one. Okay. So then, in your opinion or if you have to think about it, why do you think there are so few male APNs in the workforce? No idea. I feel like, I don't know whether this feeling is correct, but I feel that most of the public hospitals, except for IMH, the majority are female dominated, populated, I mean heavily populated by female nurses. So the only male APN interns that have interacted with are actually from IMH. So I feel that, just the fact that the profile of nurses in all the different public hospitals is mainly female dominated. Of course, that is a very known fact and a very accurate feeling. Yeah, I'm going to share some statistics with you. So at the moment, out of 100% of the RNs, 11% are male. But then, for the APN workforce, only about 5% of the workforce are males. So there is quite a discrepancy, it's not proportionate. So I'm just wondering what are your thoughts about it? Okay. I feel that because, I'm not sure if it's because the patient profile in IMH requires a more male figure. I said more male staff are deployed at IMH as compared to the rest of the public hospitals. Because to be honest, for male nurses, I feel that it is really harder to deploy them. They are less versatile in terms of manpower deployment. Because they cannot nurse female patients. But for female nurses, they are more versatile. They can manage and care for both male and female patients. So probably as a nursing manager, if you have female staff, it's less taxing on you to think about your deployment of manpower. So I guess naturally, for example, in my current work, there are 4 male staff. Actually, to plan the 3 shift roster is quite a headache. Because first of all, you must ensure that at all times, there cannot be more than 2 male staff on shift. And during night shift itself, it causes further problems. Because you cannot have 2 male nurses on shift without any female nurses. So as the person who is plotting the roster, you have to take into consideration not only the capability level of all the nurses, but also the gender. So I feel that naturally, the specialty requirement would probably affect the gender. Of course, if you say that 5% of APN workforce are male, I think the bulk of that comes from IHR. I'm not sure if we check the census of RNs in IHR, it's only 40-60% of male nurses are higher. So I think for them, out of 40% to choose appropriate candidates to become APNs, the proportion of male may be higher. I think you have a very valid point. Before I make further comments, can you share a bit more about your role in this inpatient work that you speak about? So basically, I'm a work-based APN. I'm based in our palliative ward, which is 13-bedded. The role I do there is to... Sorry, Gexin, you were broken up a bit. Maybe you can track back a few more sentences about your role in the 13-bedded ward. Okay, so the role in the ward itself, obviously I play a few roles. I think the first one is to mentor the nurses regarding palliative care knowledge. The second one is to round and see patients on a daily basis. And also to bridge the gap between the medical team and the nurses to ensure that there is more cohesive working relationship between the nursing and medical team. Maybe you can tell me about a typical day. Like for instance, maybe yesterday, what were the activities that you do? So when I come to work, I will receive a handover from the ward nurses about what happened during the night time. Any behavioural issues, any patients who are more symptomatic that require early review. Then I will see the patients together with the medical officers. Then when the consultant comes, I will run with them. At the same time, I will pull in the ward nurses to join the rounds. Then I will let them present their concerns to the medical team. And then I will try to help them understand the plan of the day. Then after, we will update families. I think because our palliative care ward has a lot of communication and high tension. I mean more high stake conversations because patients are more ill and there is more restriction in the visiting hours. So also to help the nurses to clarify misconceptions with family members. So that most of the time, the family members come after office hours and they may raise concerns to the nurses. So we also use that platform to help clarify any issues that the family has that may raise up to the nurses. So hearing your role and the activities that you play, do you think that a male APN in your context and playing your role will face any challenges? Or he would still be able to function well and function as much as you? I think he will be able to function well and probably as well. Because I feel that sometimes when you have violent patients or patients who are very delirious, I would think a male APN would be more helpful in subduing them. So in a sense, what I'm trying to get at is, I'm trying to think and compare. A male APN, they can see female patients right? I mean, what are your thoughts? Because now you're saying that as a nurse manager, you have some issues with deploying men in terms of rostering. Because that's the role of an RN, they have to take care of the basic needs of the patient. So yes, fair enough, the gender matters. But now I'm just wondering, do you think that in the role that you play, there will be limitations for the male APN? Maybe during physical examination, they definitely need a chaperone if it's a female patient. Which may then, I'm not sure whether that will hinder how fast they can see a patient. But for female APNs, if they're going chaperones, we can just go ahead and see a patient. Might be faster. So in your experience and practically, how easy is it for one to get a chaperone in your ward? It can be challenging. Because now as a female APN, I can be the one chaperoning my male medical colleagues. But now if everybody is male, then we need to probably trouble one of the female RNs to chaperone. But I guess this also wouldn't limit why we will or won't choose a male as an APN. Okay. Then do you think that there's a possibility that men are less interested in the APN role? Interest. Do you think there's a problem with interest? Interest. Because just now you shared how there are male leaders in management, in clinical and in research and you think that they excel in all these. But why in APN practice, there isn't really a male lead or more males coming in? So I'm just wondering, is it an interest thing? Maybe it might be an interest thing. Yeah, maybe. Then, off your mind now, do you think that there are barriers deterring men from pursuing the APN career track? Well, I guess it shouldn't be limiting. It shouldn't be limiting. There is actually a barrier. One is the possibility of them needing a chaperone, maybe limited practice. But apart from this, is there any more barriers that you think will be a put-off to men when they don't want to pursue this career track? I mean, maybe. I'm not sure. Maybe because they probably spent two years in NS already. They don't always spend more time studying progress. I mean, in APN, the clinical track, you need to study and then you exit from your OSCE. Then you will be able to perform the full role of APN. And then probably slowly, gradually, you will move up the career path. But I guess if it's in other career paths, then it's not limited by the qualification. Maybe you can share a bit more about that. So maybe they feel like they already, not say wasted, but they already spent two years away from studies or from work. So technically, in order to catch up or in order to progress, then they probably don't want to waste too much time pursuing something that requires one and a half years to two years to achieve. Are you implying that other tracks don't really take that long? Yeah, I don't think. For example, a CI course, it wouldn't take years, right? It probably takes months. Then for management role, I mean, probably already eased into the management role before they send you to further studies. So I guess, maybe that's one consideration. Actually, is it required for management roles to have some sort of qualification? I think no. I don't think so. But if they are interested to pursue, I would think that they will probably pursue further studies after they get into that, after they have progressed in their career already. But I guess for ATN itself, you need to study before you can progress. Okay. Why do you think men would prefer that? Like to get that position first, then maybe possibly think of further studies. Maybe they, I don't know, I think I always hear them feel that they waste two years of their life. Who waste ever? Do you think there is then any other way to improve recruitment of men into the APM profession? I don't know. I feel that for the APM role, it's definitely still capability and interest rather than anything else. Expound a bit, like why? What about capability and interest and why? I feel that spending one and a half years to study for a person to spend on. So if you don't have the interest or the… I need you to repeat again. Sorry, it was a lag. So you said to spend one and a half years to study, then what happens? So having to spend one and a half years and to progress through the role, you need a lot of… You need to know that you really… I mean, because the internship, that one year, it can be quite tedious and can be quite mentally challenging. So if you don't have the interest or you are not sure that you ultimately want to be in this clinical role, then you're going to be emotionally and physically too tiring for anyone who feels that it's not worth it to go through. So I feel that it should not be determined by whether male or female, but rather whether the person has an interest and has the capability. And capability in the sense that the clinical kind of equipment that they may have or some of them may not have in order to sign up for the course. Because that one year internship is too long drawn already and too… It can be… I mean, the psychological impact can make or break a person, I feel. I mean, how vigorous it is. So if it is not worth it to a person, then there's no point going through that whole one year. But in the first place, do you think that… Hello? You said it shouldn't be limited to… To gender lah, per se. Okay. Okay, so then it brings me to this question, which is, do you then think it's important to have more male APNs in the first place? Or status quo is fine? No. Okay, no. Why? Yes, status quo is fine. Okay, why? Why ah? I don't feel that… Because I don't feel that capability and interest or passion is related to gender. Okay. So I don't see the need to attract more male APNs for the sake that we need more male profiles. Rather, we need people who are really truly interested and passionate about what they are doing. Because I feel that if someone goes in for the sake of… Because it's more attractive to them. Just to attract males, then we do something to attract them. Then in the end, they go through the course and they are not suitable to become an APN. Then it's totally a waste of their time. 18 months plus 1 year of internship, that's like 2 and a half years. It's a waste of someone's time. And so… But then, do you think that having more men in the APN workforce will have an influence on the professional image of nursing in Singapore? No, I don't think we need… We don't need… I think gender should come into play when we want to portray professional image. Shouldn't or should? Shouldn't. Okay. Why? Because I mean… I feel that… For professional image, it means that you have to excel in the particular job you are in. So in order to excel in a particular job you are in, it's dependent on your ability and not on your gender. Okay. Yeah, so even if you are in the corporate world, even though there are more males, so if you are professional, it should be because you are good. You excel in what you do and not because you are a male. Okay. How about… Do you think that having more men in the APN workforce will have an influence on the public's perception of nursing in Singapore? I mean… Males in nursing is generally quite… I mean… Okay, I don't know if I should say this but… I mean generally, people's public perception of male nurses is that they are either more… They wouldn't see the masculine aspect of a male nurse. That's what I feel, the public perception. So I don't think it would impact the nursing profession if there are more male NPS. Okay. That's an interesting point of view. Because I would think that there is this stereotype that male is better and stronger. So if we were to have a man represent nursing, it would catch the attention of the public and all that. I mean, I personally don't feel like that. Okay, no problem. Yes, it's your views and I think they are valid. Okay, so in terms of thinking about… Let's say we want to just postulate and hypothesise that we have certain male APNs in your institution. Is there specific areas or specialties that these APNs will play a more significant role in healthcare? Because they are males. So for instance, you spoke previously earlier about how you will find a lot of male APNs in IMH. Yes. Maybe we can start the discussion from there. So maybe you can tell me why do you think there are more male APNs in IMH? I think generally IMH will recruit more males in the first place because of the profile of their patients. Okay. Yes, so to begin with, they already start with a bigger pool of male nurses. So I think the probability of getting a male APN is probably higher than any other place. Okay, so the profile of the patients, maybe you can share a bit more. Like why is it that having a male APN there will play a significant role in… So I guess among psychiatry patients, I mean they do have emotional outbursts or more agitated kind of behaviour, then probably you need someone physically more strong to manage them. Or sometimes patients with personality disorders, I think they do better with someone more commanding. Then probably a male figure may be more useful. As compared to other private hospitals where patients are physically ill, then they need the nurturing, taking care of you. Then probably the female personality may be more suited. So okay, now let's talk about your institution. In your institution, if you were to more accurately place, you have male and female APNs. You want to more accurately place the male APNs, where would you place them? In which specialty and which areas? I think chronic disease kind of profile, patients with chronic disease. Like stubborn uncle, like COPD kind, heart failure. Like you know, those kind of chronic illness, those uncles who are very stubborn, don't want to listen to the nurse kind. And why do you think having a male APN there would make a difference? So ultimately I think the older generation, I mean the profile of older generation who are mostly suffering from chronic illnesses, they still have a very strong sense of male dominance in their culture. So I feel that probably a male figure, APN, probably can exert some male dominance over them or their thoughts. I mean especially for older generation. For the younger generation where gender equality is like a very heated topic, then I don't think male or female would make a significant difference. Because our population is aging. Then a lot of our older patients suffer from chronic illnesses, and they have more stubborn kind of personality. And they are more, as in their male dominated kind of perception is more ingrained in their culture. So probably they do better with male APN, managing them. So I suppose this would be more of like outpatient setting? Yes, I mean inpatient is also possible because we do see them coming in for exacerbation. So they can be also seen in the inpatient. Okay, other than chronic disease management for stubborn patients, is there any other areas you think that you would deploy male APNs to? We had. The idea I have is that it's a very open concept, right? There's not much. It's about rehabilitation back to their original state of function. So I mean because of the open concept, there's less need for chaperone, less need for privacy kind of like state. Then probably the male APNA, I mean more convenient to have a male running the APN role there. Anywhere else? Oh, emergency department. Okay. Why? I guess, I feel that in the emergency department, maybe more fast paced. I mean the priority is to save lives. So it's more like there is a need to maintain privacy. So I guess, I mean the concept of the discipline, fast paced, there's not much privacy required for one-to-one kind of interaction. Then more suitable for the male to be in. Okay. Okay. How about, what do you think about the community? Your institution do provide some community services, right? Yes, yes. Do you think that we can deploy male APNs there? Actually, it's a good idea. I guess I kind of think about it, if we do on-call in the middle of the night for home care services that provide 24-7 coverage, then technically if males go out to see patients during the night, probably safer. Okay. Possibly. Possibly. So we spoke about the... Before that, is there any other areas that you think they can play? Not really. So just now we spoke about one disadvantage of having males in APN practice, one of which is the need for chaperone which requires additional manpower. Is there other disadvantages that you can think of? I think examination-wise, for example, if performing certain skills, like for example, inserting IVC or giving sub-procedures, or even... Because in my discipline, sometimes we see a lot of patients with breast CA and a lot of pungent wounds. So I'm not sure, certain disciplines, for example, more oncology, palliative, kind of setting, whether... Will it be difficult for the maleness to perform these procedures? Like for example, checking on the pungent wounds, the breast, or pungent wound of the vulva, where these are common female cancers. So I think that might be a limitation. Anywhere else? I mean, anything else? No... I think that's about it. Then maybe let's talk about something more positive. Is there any advantages of having male APNs around? Can you think of any advantages? Well, I guess, you know, if we need any... I guess... Advantages... Well, I guess for stubborn patients or very demanding patients, or agitated and violent, I guess the male APNs are much more... Very helpful to help the nurse to manage those agitated and violent patients. And then also, of course, managing those chronic illnesses, maybe a male figure for the older generation may do a better job. Maybe they will be able to do a better job than any other positive. I guess that's about all I can say. Okay, I'm almost coming to the end. I just have one last question to ask. Do you think that because there are so few men in the RN workforce, do you think that they are placed at a disadvantage? Like there is lesser chance of them being selected for the program or being selected for anything at all? Okay. I don't feel so in my hospital. Mainly because the selection process is objective. Because we use the MMI, so it's actually an objective way to assess clinical ability of a nurse. It's voluntary kind of sign-up. Like whoever wants to... Whoever is considering to become APN, they just need to sign up. So basically, everybody has equal chance. It's objective. But if let's say, talk about opportunities in general in the hospital, I don't feel that they are at a disadvantage. Because I still feel it's binary. Okay, before I end this interview, do you have anything else you want to speak into this topic that we have about recruiting more men into APN practice and also about the gender gap, gender disparity in the APN practice? No. Can, can. So I end the interview now, okay? Okay. Okay, I'll stop recording.
